Just finished listening to the Bittensor Guru podcast. Very interesting subnet, but I was pretty disappointed that Keith didn't ask more technical questions. I think the elephant in the room here is that distributed training is a huge challenge, right? OpenAI uses Inifiband with bandwidth in the tens of Gb/s, so wouldn't distributed training dependent on internet speed take literally CENTURIES to train? distributed training is a pretty large challenge but we should solve all blockings as we can't outperform centralized ai without it.

I don't think so. 
A) Miners running 10+ Gbps rigs is not impossible (However, we think that may or may not be necessary, I will explain below)
B) There are innovations that are developing that allow for easier training coming in all the time. 
C) By virtue of being open-source we can easily get feedback from the community, set bounties. etc.

Also the dependence of distributed training on internet speed is relevant to model size and sync/communication frequency. If we can reduce communication frequency to n updates per day. Then it becomes a question of how often miners need to communicate. Assuming a model that is 100GB is being trained by m miners, then the total bandwidth per day is m*n*model_size. At 200 miners that's 20 TB per update. Large but not impossible, especially if split over 200 miners.

Currently our main challenge has been training stability, reliability and averaging. We've had training stagnate due to failure to properly average over a large number of miners. We're currently testing our new approach for optimal averaging. Similar to Scaling laws for LLMs we're now running some tests to come up with averaging laws for distributed training. This will allow us to figure out at which points training can diverge and at which points it remains stable. Based on this information we can then determine what our options are in terms of model size, number of updates and by extension internet speed requirements.

In this release we're moving away from our previous hivemind dependent approach. We were inspired by the work of @consτ [τ, τ] as well as SN9 (pushing meta-data to chain) and 6, attempting to put the incentive mechanism to work for us rather attempting to do everything manually.
